#1. Loads and cleans the core data set to prepare for analysis.

  #We used the cleannames() function to get rid of unnecessary spaces in the column names. 

#2. Shows basic exploratory analysis to demonstrate an understanding of the dataset, including the number of rows and columns, any obvious limitations or flaws and any reasons why it might not be able to answer the questions you've posted last week. 


  #In this dataset there are 20,718 rows (different songs) with 21      columns (mostly different categories to break down the songs, though some are links). There arent any obvious flaws that stand out to us at the moment. 

  #A big limitation is that the data does not tell us the date that songs came out. This is important to know because it could be unfair to compare a song that just came out to one thats been out for years and the two are not actually equal. This data also doesnt tell us the peak height that a song reached on the Hot 100 Billboard charts which could be interesting to be aware of. It would be a bit hard to define what popular means outside of this metric, but for our case we will try to find a dataset that we think fits it to the best of our ability. 

#3. Describe the limits of the data in terms of timeframe, what is and is not included and any codes or other information you'd need to find definitions for, and what you've done to better define it.

  #The data was collected Feb 7, 2023. So right off the bat any songs   that were released after that are not on the list and any songs that gained popularity after that are not reflected properly to the numbers of today.. For the most part all the data is understandable and we wouldnt need to search for the definitions of it. The only term that I was unfamiliar with was valence but after a quick google search I learned that it means musical positiveness conveyed by a track.

# Question 1. How does the amount of energy within the music compare to the number of views the song has 

correlation_df <- spotify_youtube %>%
  filter(!is.na(energy)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(views)) %>% 
  mutate(views_energy = energy / views) %>%
  mutate(correlation = cor (energy, views))

correlation <- cor(correlation_df$energy, correlation_df$views)

print(correlation)
[1] 0.06757503
# The correlation number here shows that there is not a significant correlation between the two categories.

cor.test(correlation_df$energy, correlation_df$views)

#Question 2: Is there a connection between the length of the song and the valence (mood) of the song?

spotify_youtube <- spotify_youtube %>%
  mutate(minute_run = duration_ms / 60000) %>%
  mutate(minute_val_ratio = valence/minute_run)
  
correlation_df_minuteval <- spotify_youtube %>%
  filter(!is.na(valence)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(energy)) %>%
   mutate(correlation = cor (valence, energy))


correlation <- cor(correlation_df_minuteval$valence, correlation_df_minuteval$energy)

print(correlation)
[1] 0.3891579
# The correlation number here shows that there is not a significant correlation between the two categories.

#Question 3: What key is most frequent within the top 20 most streamed songs? What about within all the songs is in the data?
top_20 <- spotify_youtube %>%
    arrange(desc(stream))%>%
    head(25)
  
    top20_cleaned <- top_20[c (-5, -8, -11, -13, -23), ]
    
    
  spotify_youtube %>%  
  group_by(key)%>%
  summarise(total_key=n())%>%
  mutate(pct = (total_key/20718)*100)%>% 
  arrange(desc(total_key))
  

# The most common keys are C# (1), G (7) and D (2). These keys occur 5, 3 and 2 times respectively. Since the C# key occurs five times, our major finding is that the C# key is occurring about 25% of the time within the top 20 most streamed songs. Of all the songs, the most common is C which occurs 11% of the time. It is interesting to note though that  the C# key is nearly twice as common within the top 20 most streamed songs as it is within all (10% as compared to 25%).This could be because writers have noticed that songs in this key do well, or sound good so they strive to write hit songs in that key. For this story it would be interesting to look more into what exactly makes up a hit song as key could definitely play a factor in a song being more popular. Within our story we would want to pitch that we should interview songwriters with the hopes of creating a hit and ask them what goes into their decision making process and whether or not they heavily consider a songs key before creating their song.

  


#Question 4: What level of loudness is the most frequent among the top 20 streamed songs?

top20_loudness <- top20_cleaned%>%
  group_by(loudness)%>%
  summarise(total_loudness=n())%>%
  arrange(desc(total_loudness))

loudness_rounded <- top20_cleaned%>%
  mutate(loudness_rounded = round(loudness, 0))%>%
  group_by(loudness_rounded)%>%
  summarise(total_loudness_rounded = n())%>%
  arrange(desc(total_loudness_rounded))

top20_cleaned %>%
  mutate( loudness_rounded = round(loudness, 0)) %>%
    group_by(loudness_rounded)%>%
  summarise(total_loudness_rounded = n()) %>%
  mutate(pct= total_loudness_rounded/ 20 *100 ) %>%
  arrange (desc(total_loudness_rounded))




#Note: The most common level of loudness among the top 20 streamed songs is -6, -7 and -5.These key's occur 8, 4 and 2 times respectively. Since 8 out of the 20 most streamed songs have a loudness of -6, this occurs about 40% of the time. We could not figure out how loud that actually is because when we researched decibels, the measuring unit, it was a completely different scale than our data set had it as. However, this is an interesting finding because nearly half of the top 20 streamed songs in the data have the same loudness level. It would be interesting to look into why this is, if it has anything to do with the hit song production process, or if people who are streaming songs are more inclined to listen to songs within this level of loudness. 

#Question 5: Of the top 20 most streamed songs, which song has the highest like to view ratio?

top20_liketoview <- top20_cleaned%>%
  mutate(like_view = (likes / views)*100)%>%
  arrange(desc(like_view))

spotify_youtube%>%
  mutate(like_view = (likes / views)*100)%>%
  arrange(desc(like_view))



#The songs that have the highest like to view ratio are Heat Waves by Glass Animals and Stay by The Kid Laroi (feat. Justin Bieber), these songs both have approximately a 1.49% like to view ratio. This means that about 1.49% of all the people who viewed their respective music videos gave it a like on YouTube.
